is the message again: Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resem...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Here is the real-world case again:<br><br><i>Dutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it had a problem. As it shipped its products to customers, it found that many bicycles were arriving to customers damaged.<\/i><br><br><i>The damage reports were a major problem for the company because the company\u2019s bikes are high-end, and some are loaded down with delicate electronics like anti-theft trackers and electric motors. Plus, the company had set a goal to sell 90 percent of its bikes online by the end of the decade.<\/i><br><br><i>One of the employees came up with a solution: print a graphic of a flatscreen television on the side of the box. By making shippers think that they were transporting flatscreen televisions, the company found that shipping damage dropped by 70-80 percent. Nobody wants to damage a new television.<\/i><br>","DataExportTag":"Q159","QuestionID":"QID159"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID175","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the message again: Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resem...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the message again:<\/b><br \/>\n<br \/>\n<i>Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resemble those of more fragile products can reduce damages due to shipping.<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the message again: Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resem...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Here is the message again:<i><br><\/i><br>Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resemble those of more fragile products can reduce damages due to shipping.<br>","DataExportTag":"Q175","QuestionID":"QID175"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID265","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the message again: Even if you have extremely compelling evidence, people often require t...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the message again:<\/b><br>\n<br>\n<i>Even if you have extremely compelling evidence, people often require the support of an underlying theory before they will change their minds.<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the message again: Even if you have extremely compelling evidence, people often require t...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<b>Here is the message again:<\/b><br \/>\n<br \/>\n<i>Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resemble those of more fragile products can reduce damages due to shipping.<\/i>","DataExportTag":"Q265","QuestionID":"QID265"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID280","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the message again: Giving away your product to social media influencers can be an inexpen...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the message again:<\/b><br>\n<br>\n<i>Giving away your product to social media influencers can be an inexpensive but effective way of marketing.<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the message again: Giving away your product to social media influencers can be an inexpen...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<b>Here is the message again:<\/b><br \/>\n<br \/>\n<i>Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resemble those of more fragile products can reduce damages due to shipping.<\/i>","DataExportTag":"Q280","QuestionID":"QID280"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID295","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the message again: Sometimes it can be lucrative for a company to improve the simplicity...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the message again:<\/b><br>\n<br>\n<i>Sometimes it can be lucrative for a company to improve the simplicity and speed of delivery rather than improve the product itself.<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the message again: Sometimes it can be lucrative for a company to improve the simplicity...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<b>Here is the message again:<\/b><br \/>\n<br \/>\n<i>Companies that package their products in ways that superficially resemble those of more fragile products can reduce damages due to shipping.<\/i>","DataExportTag":"Q295","QuestionID":"QID295"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID67","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the professor's\u00a0real-world case again: Dutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it h..","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the professor's&nbsp;real-world case again:<\/b><br>\n<br><i>\nDutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it had a problem. As it shipped its products to customers, it found that many bicycles were arriving to customers damaged.<br>\n<br>\nThe damage reports were a major problem for the company because the company\u2019s bikes are high-end, and some are loaded down with delicate electronics like anti-theft trackers and electric motors. Plus, the company had set a goal to sell 90 percent of its bikes online by the end of the decade.<br>\n<br>\nOne of the employees came up with a solution: print a graphic of a flatscreen television on the side of the box. By making shippers think that they were transporting flatscreen televisions, the company found that shipping damage dropped by 70-80 percent. Nobody wants to damage a new television.<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"DataExportTag":"general","QuestionID":"QID67","QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the professor's\u00a0real-world case again: Dutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it h...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID142","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the real-world case again: In 1843, Dr. Semmelweis noticed a 3 to 1 imbalance in deaths d...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the real-world case again:<\/b><br><br><i>In 1843, Dr. Semmelweis noticed a 3 to 1 imbalance in deaths due to childbirth at one hospital compared to another. He performed experiments and was able to prove that the problem was that doctors in one hospital were not washing their hands. He then showed the hospital his data, but no one listened. It was only with the widespread adoption of germ theory (decades later), which supported his findings that all doctors began washing hands.<\/i><br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the real-world case again: In 1843, Dr. Semmelweis noticed a 3 to 1 imbalance in deaths d...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"Here is the real-world case again:<br><br><i>Dutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it had a problem. As it shipped its products to customers, it found that many bicycles were arriving to customers damaged.<\/i><br><br><i>The damage reports were a major problem for the company because the company\u2019s bikes are high-end, and some are loaded down with delicate electronics like anti-theft trackers and electric motors. Plus, the company had set a goal to sell 90 percent of its bikes online by the end of the decade.<\/i><br><br><i>One of the employees came up with a solution: print a graphic of a flatscreen television on the side of the box. By making shippers think that they were transporting flatscreen televisions, the company found that shipping damage dropped by 70-80 percent. Nobody wants to damage a new television.<\/i><br>","DataExportTag":"Q142","QuestionID":"QID142"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID250","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the real-world case again: In 2008, Dominos was suffering from the Great Recession and th...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the real-world case again:<\/b><br><br><i>In 2008, Dominos was suffering from the Great Recession and the general consensus that their pizza was low quality. Instead of improving their pizza, they created a sales system that optimized ordering and delivery. Customers could customize their pizza online or through an app, and save their preferences. Because of this, from 2008 to 2020 their stock rose from $2.83 to $433.78.<\/i><br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the real-world case again: In 2008, Dominos was suffering from the Great Recession and th...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<b>Here is the real-world case again:<\/b><br><br><i>Dutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it had a problem. As it shipped its products to customers, it found that many bicycles were arriving to customers damaged.<\/i><br><br><i>The damage reports were a major problem for the company because the company\u2019s bikes are high-end, and some are loaded down with delicate electronics like anti-theft trackers and electric motors. Plus, the company had set a goal to sell 90 percent of its bikes online by the end of the decade.<\/i><br><br><i>One of the employees came up with a solution: print a graphic of a flatscreen television on the side of the box. By making shippers think that they were transporting flatscreen televisions, the company found that shipping damage dropped by 70-80 percent. Nobody wants to damage a new television.<\/i><br>","DataExportTag":"Q250","QuestionID":"QID250"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID242","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the real-world case again: In 2016, Jean-Philippe Courtois was put in charge of Microsoft...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the real-world case again:<\/b><br><br><i>In 2016, Jean-Philippe Courtois was put in charge of Microsoft\u2019s global sales and operations (over 40,000 people) as the company shifted to cloud based software. To best accommodate this change, Courtois decided to replace the company\u2019s training on anticipating customer questions with training on listening to customers, and scrapped lengthy performance reviews for coaching opportunities on interpersonal skills. Despite a huge transition to a cloud-based infrastructure, Microsoft saw a $19 million rise in revenue from 2016 to 2018 \u2013 mostly thanks to satisfied customers.<\/i><br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the real-world case again: In 2016, Jean-Philippe Courtois was put in charge of Microsoft...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<b>Here is the real-world case again:<\/b><br><br><i>Dutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it had a problem. As it shipped its products to customers, it found that many bicycles were arriving to customers damaged.<\/i><br><br><i>The damage reports were a major problem for the company because the company\u2019s bikes are high-end, and some are loaded down with delicate electronics like anti-theft trackers and electric motors. Plus, the company had set a goal to sell 90 percent of its bikes online by the end of the decade.<\/i><br><br><i>One of the employees came up with a solution: print a graphic of a flatscreen television on the side of the box. By making shippers think that they were transporting flatscreen televisions, the company found that shipping damage dropped by 70-80 percent. Nobody wants to damage a new television.<\/i><br>","DataExportTag":"Q242","QuestionID":"QID242"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID234","SecondaryAttribute":"Here is the real-world case again: The Edwards family pooled $35,000 of their own money to produc...","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<b>Here is the real-world case again:<\/b><br><br><i>The Edwards family pooled $35,000 of their own money to produce their homeopathic cure for constipation: the Squatty Potty. With no money left to market the Potty, the family decided to simply give it away to various health media influencers on Instagram, Facebook, and Twitter. Despite spending no money on advertising, sales of the product quickly rose to $28,000, and caught the attention of Dr. Oz, Howard Stern, and Shark Tank, bringing Squatty Potty to an annual revenue of $12 million.<\/i><br>","DefaultChoices":false,"QuestionType":"DB","Selector":"TB","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText"},"QuestionDescription":"Here is the real-world case again: The Edwards family pooled $35,000 of their own money to produc...","ChoiceOrder":[],"Validation":{"Settings":{"Type":"None"}},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":4,"NextAnswerId":1,"QuestionText_Unsafe":"<b>Here is the real-world case again:<\/b><br><br><i>Dutch bicycle manufacturer VanMoof found that it had a problem. As it shipped its products to customers, it found that many bicycles were arriving to customers damaged.<\/i><br><br><i>The damage reports were a major problem for the company because the company\u2019s bikes are high-end, and some are loaded down with delicate electronics like anti-theft trackers and electric motors. Plus, the company had set a goal to sell 90 percent of its bikes online by the end of the decade.<\/i><br><br><i>One of the employees came up with a solution: print a graphic of a flatscreen television on the side of the box. By making shippers think that they were transporting flatscreen televisions, the company found that shipping damage dropped by 70-80 percent. Nobody wants to damage a new television.<\/i><br>","DataExportTag":"Q234","QuestionID":"QID234"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID99","SecondaryAttribute":"How big is the takeaway for you?","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<i>How big is the takeaway for you?<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"DataExportTag":"t.g2","QuestionType":"MC","Selector":"SAHR","SubSelector":"TX","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","LabelPosition":"BELOW"},"QuestionDescription":"How big is the takeaway for you?","Choices":{"2":{"Display":"Very small"},"3":{"Display":"Small"},"4":{"Display":"Somewhat small"},"5":{"Display":"Neither small nor big"},"7":{"Display":"Somewhat big"},"8":{"Display":"Big"},"9":{"Display":"Very big"}},"ChoiceOrder":["2","3","4","5","7","8","9"],"Validation":{"Settings":{"ForceResponse":"ON","ForceResponseType":"ON","Type":"None"}},"RecodeValues":{"2":"1","3":"2","4":"3","5":"4","7":"5","8":"6","9":"7"},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":10,"NextAnswerId":3,"QuestionID":"QID99"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID104","SecondaryAttribute":"How big is the takeaway for you?","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<i>How big is the takeaway for you?<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"DataExportTag":"t.r","QuestionType":"MC","Selector":"SAHR","SubSelector":"TX","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","LabelPosition":"BELOW"},"QuestionDescription":"How big is the takeaway for you?","Choices":{"2":{"Display":"Very small"},"3":{"Display":"Small"},"4":{"Display":"Somewhat small"},"5":{"Display":"Neither small nor big"},"7":{"Display":"Somewhat big"},"8":{"Display":"Big"},"9":{"Display":"Very big"}},"ChoiceOrder":["2","3","4","5","7","8","9"],"Validation":{"Settings":{"ForceResponse":"ON","ForceResponseType":"ON","Type":"None"}},"RecodeValues":{"2":"1","3":"2","4":"3","5":"4","7":"5","8":"6","9":"7"},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":10,"NextAnswerId":3,"QuestionID":"QID104"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID109","SecondaryAttribute":"How big is the takeaway for you?","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<i>How big is the takeaway for you?<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"DataExportTag":"t.h","QuestionType":"MC","Selector":"SAHR","SubSelector":"TX","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","LabelPosition":"BELOW"},"QuestionDescription":"How big is the takeaway for you?","Choices":{"2":{"Display":"Very small"},"3":{"Display":"Small"},"4":{"Display":"Somewhat small"},"5":{"Display":"Neither small nor big"},"7":{"Display":"Somewhat big"},"8":{"Display":"Big"},"9":{"Display":"Very big"}},"ChoiceOrder":["2","3","4","5","7","8","9"],"Validation":{"Settings":{"ForceResponse":"ON","ForceResponseType":"ON","Type":"None"}},"RecodeValues":{"2":"1","3":"2","4":"3","5":"4","7":"5","8":"6","9":"7"},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":10,"NextAnswerId":3,"QuestionID":"QID109"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID114","SecondaryAttribute":"How big is the takeaway for you?","TertiaryAttribute":null,"Payload":{"QuestionText":"<i>How big is the takeaway for you?<\/i>","DefaultChoices":false,"DataExportTag":"t.g","QuestionType":"MC","Selector":"SAHR","SubSelector":"TX","DataVisibility":{"Private":false,"Hidden":false},"Configuration":{"QuestionDescriptionOption":"UseText","LabelPosition":"BELOW"},"QuestionDescription":"How big is the takeaway for you?","Choices":{"2":{"Display":"Very small"},"3":{"Display":"Small"},"4":{"Display":"Somewhat small"},"5":{"Display":"Neither small nor big"},"7":{"Display":"Somewhat big"},"8":{"Display":"Big"},"9":{"Display":"Very big"}},"ChoiceOrder":["2","3","4","5","7","8","9"],"Validation":{"Settings":{"ForceResponse":"ON","ForceResponseType":"ON","Type":"None"}},"RecodeValues":{"2":"1","3":"2","4":"3","5":"4","7":"5","8":"6","9":"7"},"GradingData":[],"Language":[],"NextChoiceId":10,"NextAnswerId":3,"QuestionID":"QID114"}},{"SurveyID":"SV_9SsLUX1YLBxRm6i","Element":"SQ","PrimaryAttribute":"QID119","SecondaryAttribute":"How big is the takeaway for you?","TertiaryAttribute":null,